>
  <h2>The problem</h2>
  <p>Every time a VLM sees an image, it runs it through a full CLIP encoder pass. In video streams or multi-turn conversations where the same frame keeps appearing, that's a lot of compute going toward producing the exact same embedding you already computed two seconds ago. Nobody was caching this, so I built a cache.</p>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <p>The cache has three layers, each handling a different kind of redundancy. The first layer hashes the raw image bytes with blake2b and checks for an exact match — if two images are byte-for-byte identical, skip encoding entirely and return the cached embedding. The second layer runs FAISS cosine similarity over stored embeddings; if an incoming image's embedding is close enough to something already cached, it reuses that result too. The third layer is a small MLP trained to classify whether two embeddings represent a genuine context shift or just a near-duplicate, so a similarity hit that actually belongs to a different moment in the conversation doesn't get served stale.</p>

  <h2>What I found</h2>
  <p>On a synthetic benchmark — 100 base images replayed with exact repeats and cropped near-duplicates — the full three-layer cache resolved 37.5% of queries from cache, versus 31.25% for a naive exact-hash-only cache: a real gain from adding similarity search on top of hashing. The drift-detection layer, evaluated separately, classifies genuine context drift at 78% accuracy — solid, but the benchmark's query sequence doesn't yet include a scenario built to exercise it, so it never actually fired during this run. The bigger lesson was methodological: measuring whether a cache is worth it means benchmarking against the cost it's meant to avoid — repeated CLIP encoding — not just the lookup overhead, and the current benchmark only measures the latter.</p>
